 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 876<br> <font color=#333333>(8/27/03 2:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=323.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cha</span><hr size=1> Fact is, copyright law in its current form is a joke, and completely unecessary.  Several governments (China for example) managed to get along without it just fine, or with a far reduced period of protection.  The only purpose of the law in its current form is to make rich people richer.  <br>
<br>
Currently in the record industry, the majority of money bands make is from touring and endorsements NOT record/CD sales.  Those sales make *record companies* money.  Currently this is justified because record companies with the money are able to finance tours, sign artists, *produce* records and otherwise peform a number of duties that have become their &quot;niche&quot;.  <br>
<br>
What it also means is that the promotion of artists is based on trends and pure capitalism- people to an extent will buy what they're told to buy (Britney, Timberlake, similar talentless droolbucket users).  Record companies will only promote artists that *THEY* think will make money- one hit wonders are prime examples of artists that didn't end up making record companies money and thus were sidelined.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately there are countless examples under the current system of artists (perhaps very talented ones) who aren't making it to the big stage.  Were the decision not to lie in the hands of record executives, could the system be fairer?<br>
<br>
That is to say, if the period for copyright protection on music under the law were to be reduced, or even abolished, and record companies were no longer in charge of promoting artists, but some other body(say the artists themselves), would it not help to promote music in general?  Rather than selectively promoting a few artists at the expense of the many, we would have a system where artists could compete equally for our money without record companies deciding what music *we* should listen to.<br>
<br>
There are apparently, a lot of other very good reasons that have put forward for abolishing copyright law, explored by people far more knowledgeable than I.  Some of these people are copyright lawyers *themselves*.  Presumably, if someone is arguing for the abolition of an entire specialty (their own) within a subject, there's a good reason for that.<br>
<br>
We shouldn't be discussing distribution, rather we should be abolishing the idea of copyright periods of protection.  That would take the unreasonable power of promotive decision-making out of the hands of record executives who have been abusing the system for half a century.<br>
<br>
/end rant<br>
<br>
